informal_proof:
Let $\overline{\mathbb{Q}}$ denote the algebraic closure of $\mathbb{Q}$ in $\mathbb{C}$. The complex numbers $\mathbb{C}$ can be viewed as a transcendental extension of $\overline{\mathbb{Q}}$. By Zorn's Lemma, there exists a transcendence basis $S \subset \mathbb{C}$ over $\overline{\mathbb{Q}}$ with $|S| = 2^{\aleph_0}$. Notably, this basis contains infinitely many algebraically independent transcendental elements.

For any finite permutation $\sigma$ of distinct elements in the transcendence basis $S$, we may construct a unique automorphism as follows:

\begin{itemize}
    \item Fix an enumeration $\{s_1, s_2, s_3, ...\} \subset S$ (using a countable subset of $S$);
    \item For each $n \in \mathbb{N}$, define $\sigma_n$ as the transposition swapping $s_n$ and $s_{n+1}$ while fixing all other elements.
\end{itemize}

Each $\sigma_n$ induces a unique automorphism of $\overline{\mathbb{Q}}(S)$ by:
\begin{align*}
    \tilde{\sigma}_n: \overline{\mathbb{Q}}(S) &\to \overline{\mathbb{Q}}(S) \\
    f(s_1, ..., s_n, s_{n+1}, ...) &\mapsto f(s_1, ..., s_{n+1}, s_n, ...)
\end{align*}
where $f$ is a rational function with coefficients in $\overline{\mathbb{Q}}$.

Since $\mathbb{C}$ is the algebraic closure of $\overline{\mathbb{Q}}(S)$, each automorphism $\tilde{\sigma}_n$ extends uniquely to an automorphism $\hat{\sigma}_n$ of $\mathbb{C}$ by algebraic continuation. Specifically:
\begin{itemize}
    \item For $\alpha \in \mathbb{C}$ algebraic over $\overline{\mathbb{Q}}(S)$, map it to the conjugate root of its minimal polynomial under $\tilde{\sigma}_n$;
    \item The automorphism preserves field operations by construction.
\end{itemize}

The infinite collection $\{\hat{\sigma}_n\}_{n\in\mathbb{N}}$ consists of distinct automorphisms because:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $\hat{\sigma}_m(s_n) \neq \hat{\sigma}_k(s_n)$ for $m \neq k$ when $n = \min(m,k)$;
    \item Each transposition generates a unique permutation pattern.
\end{itemize}

Thus $\operatorname{Aut}(\mathbb{C})$ contains infinitely many distinct automorphisms. Moreover, using Cantor's diagonal argument, one can show $|\operatorname{Aut}(\mathbb{C})| = 2^{2^{\aleph_0}}$, but our construction already suffices to prove infiniteness.

$\impliedby$: \begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Separability:}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Let $q = p^m$ where $p$ is prime. If $q \equiv 1 \pmod{n}$ then $q-1$ is divisible by $n$, hence $\gcd(n,p) = 1$.
        \item The polynomial $f(x) = x^n - t$ is irreducible over $\mathbb{F}_q(t)$ by Eisenstein's criterion.
        \item The derivative $f'(x) = nx^{n-1} \neq 0$ in $\mathbb{F}_q(t)$ since $p \nmid n$, proving $f(x)$ is separable.
    \end{itemize}

    \item \textbf{Normality:}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item From $q \equiv 1 \pmod{n}$, $\mathbb{F}_q^\times$ contains all $n^\text{th}$ roots of unity.
        \item The splitting field of $x^n - t$ is $\mathbb{F}_q(t^{1/n})$, as roots are $\zeta \cdot t^{1/n}$ ($\zeta \in \mathbb{F}_q$).
    \end{itemize}
\end{enumerate}

$\implies$: \begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Separability requirement:}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item If the extension is Galois, $x^n - t$ must be separable. This forces $\gcd(n,p) = 1$, as $f'(x) = 0$ would otherwise imply $p \mid n$.
    \end{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Normality requirement:}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item For $\mathbb{F}_q(t^{1/n})$ to contain all roots of $x^n - t$, $\mathbb{F}_q$ must contain all $n^\text{th}$ roots of unity.
        \item This requires $n \mid (q-1) \implies q \equiv 1 \pmod{n}$.
    \end{itemize}
\end{enumerate}

informal_statement:
Let \( M \) be an \( R \)-module. The following are equivalent:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \( M \) is finitely generated.
    \item For every family \( (Q_{\alpha})_{\alpha \in A} \) of \( R \)-modules, the canonical map \( M \otimes_{R} \left( \prod_{\alpha} Q_{\alpha} \right) \to \prod_{\alpha} (M \otimes_{R} Q_{\alpha}) \) is surjective.
\end{enumerate}

